@node Intro "Introduction"

  @{b}@{u}Introduction to Onyx Prelude@{uu}@{ub}

   This is a new fresh mixer for the Prelude sound cards!

   It works with both the Zorro and the clock-port version
   of the Prelude.


@endnode

@node Reqs "Requirements"

  @{b}@{u}What you need to be able to run Onyx Prelude@{uu}@{ub}

   A Prelude sound card. (You can try the program without a Prelude though..)

   OS version 37+

   MUI - Magical User Interface v3.x+

   ASL.library  v38+
   MathIEEESingbas.library v33+


@endnode

@node Inst "Installation"

  @{b}@{u}How to get Onyx Prelude into your system!@{uu}@{ub}

   The most conveniet way to start it is just to copy it
   to WBStartup. If you are using another mixer you can
   remove it now because Onyx Prelude replaces any other
   mixer. It can work in parallel though if you want..


@endnode

@node Usage "Usage"

  @{b}@{u}Usage of Onyx Prelude@{uu}@{ub}

   When you first start it, it will reset the Prelude if no other
   program is using it and set the volumes to some default values
   or your saved values if you have used the program before and
   saved the settings.
   If another program already uses the sound card, like another
   mixer or a player or something, Onyx Prelude will read the
   volume settings from the Prelude and set its sliders accordingly
   without resetting the card.

   There are two different kinds of mixer windows. One smaller
   with horizontal sliders and a mute checkmark for every channel
   and one larger with vertical sliders and balance control and
   mute checkmark. The one with the vertical sliders is the most
   known type of mixers.

   All windows have the same menu which looks like follows:

   @{b}@{u}Project@{uu}@{ub}

     @{b}Open small mixer@{ub}
       This will open the smaller mixer window with the horizontal
       volume sliders.

     @{b}Open large mixer@{ub}
       This will open the larger mixer window with the vertical
       volume sliders and balance control.

     @{b}About@{ub}
       Opens an about-requester for Onyx Prelude.

     @{b}Onyxsoft@{ub}
       Opens an info-requester about Onyxsoft.

     @{b}Reset card@{ub}
       This will reset the proelude. If another program is using the
       card already you will first be asked if you are sure you want
       to reset it.

     @{b}Quit@{ub}
       Quit Onyx Prelude. A confirmation requester will open.


   @{b}@{u}Settings@{uu}@{ub}

     @{b}Onyx Prelude settings...@{ub}
       This will open the window with all settings for Onyx Prelude.
       See below for information about all things in this window.

     @{b}MUI Settings...@{ub}
       Open the standard MUI configuration window.

     @{b}Snapshot windows@{ub}
       Use this to save the mixer windows' positions and sizes.

     @{b}Save settings@{ub}
       Use this to save the settings including volume, balance
       and mute settings.

     @{b}Last saved@{ub}
       Reload the last saved settings.


   @{b}@{u}Channels@{uu}@{ub}

     This menu contains a list of all channels on the sound card.
     A channel with a checkmark is visible in the mixer windows.
     You can click on these channels to show and hide them as
     you like.


   @{fg fill}~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{fg text}

   Now follows descriptions of everything in the settings window.
   There are three pages in this window:

   @{b}@{u}Features@{ub}@{uu}

     @{b}Reset Prelude at startup@{ub}
       If you set this then the sound card will be reset when
       Onyx Prelude starts, but only if Onyx Prelude is the
       first program to open the prelude.library! This means
       that it is always safe to start Onyx Prelude while
       playing sounds even with this switch on.

     @{b}Open mixer window at startup@{ub}
       With this set the default mixer (see GUI page) will
       open when Onyx Prelude is started.

     @{b}Open mixer on volume change hotkey@{ub}
       With this switch on the mixer or a popup window will
       open everytime you press one of the master volume
       hotkeys.

     @{b}Close mixer after volume change hotkey@{ub}
       If this is set, whatever popped up will close again
       after a delay. Quite practical.

     @{b}Open popup on volume up/down arexx event@{ub}
       Same as for the volume hotkey but this is for arexx.
       Useful if you want to see the volume change if you're
       using a remote control via arexx.

     @{b}Close popup on volume up/down arexx event@{ub}
       Same as for volume hotkey.

     @{b}Close popup delay@{ub}
       This is the delay from a popup is opened until it closes.
       The time is in steps of 1/10th of a second. A value of 13
       hence means 1.3 seconds.

     @{b}+3dB volume boost@{ub}
       This will enable the Prelude's own +3 decibel volume
       boost in hardware.

     @{b}IRQ size@{ub}
       The amount to be transferred in every interrupt by the
       prelude soundcard driver.

     @{b}Input Source@{ub}
       Here you can set which channel should be the default
       input for sampling. the left and right input can be set
       independently but if you change the left channel both
       will be affected in the GUI.


   @{b}@{u}Hotkeys@{ub}@{uu}

     @{b}@{fg shine}Program Hotkeys@{fg text}@{ub}

     @{b}Open popup hotkey@{ub}
       This is the hotkey to open the mixer window. This is
       not affected by the delayed auto-close feature.

     @{b}Toggle +3dB boost hotkey@{ub}
       This is the hotkey to toggle the +dB boost.

     @{b}@{fg shine}Hotkeys for volume control@{fg text}@{ub}

       Here you can define hotkeys to control all channels
       on the prelude.

       @{u}Channel@{uu}
         What channel to control. See the documentation for
         your prelude sound card for what these different
         channels are.

       @{u}Down@{uu}
         Step the volume down.

       @{u}Up@{uu}
         Step the volume up.

       @{u}Mute@{uu}
         Toggle the channel between mute and not muted.
         Note. Muted is not the same as the lowest volume
         which is -31dB.


   @{b}@{u}GUI@{ub}@{uu}

     This page contains most settings to control the look of
     the mixers.

     @{b}@{fg shine}Volume display@{fg text}@{ub}

       @{b}Decibel@{ub}
         If this is selected a %d in a volume display string
         will be replaced with a value between -31 (lowst
         volume) and 0 (highest volume) which is the volume
         displayed in decibel (dB).

       @{b}Percent@{ub}
         If this is selected a %d in a volume display string
         will be replaced with a value between 0 (lowst
         volume) and 100 (highest volume) which is the
         volume displayed in percent (%).


     @{b}@{fg shine}Type of mixer@{fg text}@{ub}

       @{b}Small, horizontal sliders@{ub}
         This will open the smaller mixer with horizontal
         sliders when you press a hotkey to open a mixer.
         Even if you have set the other mixer as default,
         you can still open this too from the menu if you
         want to use it.

       @{b}Large, vertical sliders@{ub}
         This will open the larger mixer with vertical
         sliders and balance control when you press a hotkey
         to open a mixer. Even if you have set the other
         mixer as default, you can still open this too 
         from the menue if you want to use it.


     @{b}@{fg shine}The mixer@{fg text}@{ub}

       Here you can make some settings for the mixer. Which
       channels to show, what they should display etc. These
       settings are used for both mixers, except the @{u}Show@{uu}
       setting which is only used by the smaller mixer.

       @{u}Channel@{uu}
         Which channel the gadgets to the right control.

       @{u}Show@{uu}
         If this channel should be visible in the mixer window.

       @{u}Mstr@{uu}
         To detach a channel from the master volume, just
         uncheck the corresponding checkmark in this column.

       @{u}Slider knob@{uu}
         When using the small mixer every slider has a text
         in the knob of the slider. This is that text.
         Useful is ofcourse to put a hint of which channel
         this is as the small mixer doesn't have any
         other text displayed. This way you can also
         rename a channel if you're f.ex. using Aux 2 for
         Amiga Paula audio.
         This text should also include a  %d  if you want
         to be able to see the current level of this
         channel. %d will be replaced by a number between
         -31 and 0 if you use Decibel and 0 to 100 if you
         use Percent as volume display.

       @{u}Key@{uu}
         Here the hotkey for the slider can be configured.
         This is a single-key hotkey that works only when
         the window is active.
         Useful if you always have the mixer window open
         and don't want to define any global hotkeys.
         You should define a letter. This letter will then
         be used to increase the volume. To decrease the
         volume you use Shift + this letter. This is a
         feature of MUI, nothing I can change.
         You can also use Tab to step through the gadgets
         as usual and then use the arrow keys to change
         the volume of the active slider.
         Master volume is by default the active gadget.

       @{u}Step@{uu}
         Controls how many steps the hotkey and arexx should
         take when changing volume. This is not used when
         using the mouse or the @{u}Key@{uu} to control the
         sliders directly in the mixer window.


   @{b}@{u}Volume popup@{ub}@{uu}

     Here the behaviour of the popup window can be configured.

     Note: The popup window is not a MUI window and is therefor
     alot faster to open and close than a MUI window.
     It will also always popup on the active screen which not
     necessarily is the one you have configured Onyx Prelude
     for in the MUI settings.

     This popup window will always close after a delay. It
     can not be configured to stay open as the mixer window
     can if you use that as popup instead.

     @{b}@{fg shine}Volume event@{fg text}@{ub}

       @{b}Use mixer window@{ub}
         Select if the mixer window should popup as volume
         display on hokey or arexx event.

       @{b}Use popup window@{ub}
         Select if the popup window should popup as volume
         display on hokey or arexx event.


     @{b}@{fg shine}Popup window@{fg text}@{ub}
       
       @{b}Normal@{ub}
         Select this if the popup window should have a
         normal window border.

       @{b}Borderless@{ub}
         Select this if you want to make the window very
         slim or just to make it not look like a window.


     @{b}@{fg shine}Popup bevel@{fg text}@{ub}

       @{b}No bevel@{ub}
         Select this to make the gauge display flat and
         simple.

       @{b}Use bevel@{ub}
         Use a raised and lowered bevel around the volume
         display gauge to make it look less flat.


     @{b}Popup display@{ub}
       A string to be displayed ontop of the gauge in the
       popup window. This string can contain a %d to display
       the level. See @{u}Slider knob@{uu} for more info.
       If you clear this text you can resize the window
       anyway you want, else it will be locked to the
       height of the screen font which is the font used.

     @{b}Clear@{ub}
       A quick way of clearing the popup display string
       so that you can resize the popup window any way
       you like.

     @{b}Place pop win@{ub}
       This will open a demonstration window of where and
       how large the popup window will be that you can move
       and size as you please. Press this button again to
       close it.
       There are also four number fields to the left of this
       button that will be updated with the actual pixel
       positions of the popup window. You can also change
       these values manually if you want.

     @{b}@{fg shine}Popup window colors@{fg text}@{ub}

       Here you can set the colors of the gauge in the
       popup window to your special preferences. Pens
       for the colors will be allocated with Image
       Precision everytime the popup window opens.
       This may result in that the colors may change
       slightly from popup to popup if the system is
       short on pens on the particular screen the popup
       happens to open up on.

       Click on one of the colors below to edit that color.

       @{fg shine}Master Gauge@{fg text}
         The color of the master volume gauge.

       @{b}Swap@{ub}
         Swap the Master Gauge and the Other Gauge colors.

       @{fg shine}Other Gauge@{fg text}
         The color of the other channels gauge's.

       @{b}Swap@{ub}
         Swap the Other Gauge and Background colors.

       @{fg shine}Background@{fg text}
         The color of the background the gauge operates on.

       @{b}Sawp@{ub}
         Swap the Background and Text colors.

       @{fg shine}Text@{fg text}
         The color of the popup display text string, if it
         is used.



   @{b}Save@{ub}
     Save the settings (to ENVARC:) and close the settings
     window.

   @{b}Use@{ub}
     Use these settings (save to ENV:) and close the
     settings window.

   @{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Cancel the changes you have made and revert to how
     it was before you opened the settings window.
     (load from ENV:)


@endnode

@node Arexx "Arexx"

  @{fg shine}@{b}The arexx interface of Onyx Prelude
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   Onyx Prelude has a collection of arexx command that you
   can use to control the mixer "from underneath".
   There are no commands to control the program itself,
   like the GUI and such except for the standard MUI
   commands SHOW, HIDE, QUIT.

   All *UP and *DOWN commands step the amount up or down
   that you have configured in Settings/GUI/Step.

   Note: I use the names channel and unit interchangable.
         For the balance though channel also means left or
         right channel of a channel or unit.

   @{b}VOLUP/S@{ub}        - Step up the master volume.
   @{b}VOLDOWN/S@{ub}      - Step down the master volume.
   @{b}LINEUP/S@{ub}       - Step up the line in volume.
   @{b}LINEDOWN/S@{ub}     - Step down the line in volume.
   @{b}AUX1UP/S@{ub}       - Step up the auxiliary 1 volume.
   @{b}AUX1DOWN/S@{ub}     - Step down the auxiliary 1 volume.
   @{b}AUX2UP/S@{ub}       - Step up the auxiliary 2 volume.
   @{b}AUX2DOWN/S@{ub}     - Step down the auxiliary 2 volume.
   @{b}WAVEUP/S@{ub}       - Step up the wave DAC volume.
   @{b}WAVEDOWN/S@{ub}     - Step down the wave DAC volume.
   @{b}MONOUP/S@{ub}       - Step up the mono volume.
   @{b}MONODOWN/S@{ub}     - Step down the mono volume.
   @{b}LOOPBACKUP/S@{ub}   - Step up the loopback volume.
   @{b}LOOPBACKDOWN/S@{ub} - Step down the loopback volume.

   @{b}SETVOL U=UNIT/K/A V=VOLUME/N/A@{ub}
     This is used to set the volume of a specific channel
     or unit. The UNITs are:
       MASTER, LINE, AUX1, AUX2, WAVE, MONO and LOOPBACK.

     The volume is set either in decibel of percent depending
     of what you have selected as volume display in the
     settings.
     If using decibel the values are between -31 and 0
     where -31 is the lowest volume and 0 is maximum volume.
     If using persent, 0 is lowest volume (although not
     silent) and 100 is maximum volume.

   @{b}GETVOL U=UNIT/K/A@{ub}
     This will return the volume for a specific channel
     (or unit). The value returned will be either in decibel
     or percent depending on your preferences in the settings.
     The UNIT names are the same as for SETVOL.

   @{b}SETBALANCE U=UNIT/K/A B=BALANCE/N/A@{ub}
     This will set the balance for a specific channel or unit.
     The BALANCE value is between -31 to 0 to +31 or from
     -100 to 0 to +100 depending on your volume display
     preferences.
     A negative value means that the right channel is lowered
     while the left channel maintains the same volume.
     A positive value means that the left channel is lowered
     while the right channel maintains the same volume.
     Zero means centered balance.
     The UNIT is the same as for SETVOL.

   @{b}GETBALANCE U=UNIT/K/A@{ub}
     This will get the current balance of a specific channel
     or unit. The value returned will be between -31 and +31
     or -100 to +100 depending on your volume display
     preferences.
     Zero means that the balance is centered.
     The UNIT is the same as for SETVOL.

   @{b}MUTE U=UNIT/K/A T=TRUE/N@{ub}
     This will mute or unmute a channel.
     TRUE should be '1' to mute the channel and must be '0'
     to unmute it. TRUE can also be omitted if toggling is
     preferred.
     The UNIT is the same as for SETVOL.


@endnode

@node History "History"

  @{fg shine}@{b}What's new and what Onyx Prelude already features!
  ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~@{ub}@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Added a hotkey for the +3dB boost function which can't be
           set at startup for some reason.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Updated the layout of the prefs window a bit.

   @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Fixed a hit when adjusting the edit-popwindow.

   @{fg fill}* FIX *@{fg text} Now closing the edit-popwindow when closing the prefs.

   @{fg fill}* NEW *@{fg text} Now defaultng to the vertical mixer window.


  @{fg shine}v1.1
  ~~~~@{fg text}
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can set how many steps each volume should step
     when controlled via arexx or hotkey up/down events.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now you can get that nice popup also for the other
     channels, not just the master volume!
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now it's possible to set what channel should be used
     for input when sampling.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now the IRQ size can be set.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Now channels can be excluded from the master volume!

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The reset and update of the volume was not perfect on startup.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The arexx command MUTE can now toggle mute/no mute
     on a channel.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} The mixer window doesn't close and open everytime you
     exit the prefs, only when relevant settings have been
     changed.

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Added a SAFEMODE/S startup switch which can be used if
     you get stuck and need manual control over every critical
     thing happening during startup, such as reset of the
     card, if MUI should use Single Mode, if commodities
     should be initiated etc.
   
   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} Fixed some enforcer hits caused when using the program
     in demo mode, without a prelude card.


  @{fg shine}v1.0
  ~~~~@{fg text}

   @{fg fill}*@{fg text} First release!


@endnode

